 {"id":"br-aazao.13","title":"Verification Coverage 5.2: final claim check and exception register for remaining non-real tests","description":"# Verification Coverage 5.2: Final Claim Check and Exception Register for Remaining Non-Real Tests\n\n## Why\nThe whole point of this program is to make verification claims honest. At the end, the repo should have an explicit statement of what is truly covered, what still uses sanctioned substitutes, and why those exceptions remain.\n\n## Deliverables\n- produce a final claim check that answers:\n  - what is covered by real-path unit tests\n  - what is covered by realistic E2E tests\n  - what still relies on substitutes, fixtures, mocks, or stubs\n  - why those exceptions remain and what risk they imply\n- produce an exception register with owner, rationale, and future-removal guidance for every remaining sanctioned substitute\n- reject any vague “looks good” sign-off language in favor of specific claims tied to the verification ledger\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- future maintainers can answer the user’s original question quickly and truthfully from project artifacts rather than memory\n- any remaining substitute-based coverage is visible and justified\n- the project can distinguish “broad test count” from “credible coverage claim” in a defensible way\n\n## Important Notes\nThis is the anti-hand-waving bead. If this cannot be completed honestly, the earlier beads are not done.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":240,"created_at":"2026-03-18T13:53:19.215229439Z","created_by":"CrimsonSnow","updated_at":"2026-03-18T13:53:19.215229439Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["coverage","repo-wide","signoff","testing","verification"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-aazao.13","depends_on_id":"br-aazao","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-18T13:53:19.215229439Z","created_by":"CrimsonSnow","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"br-aazao.14","title":"Verification Coverage 4.4: failure, recovery, stress, and performance E2E matrix completion","description":"# Verification Coverage 4.4: Failure, Recovery, Stress, and Performance E2E Matrix Completion\n\n## Why\nThe existing suite surface does not yet justify a claim that the system is comprehensively tested under failure, restart, recovery, concurrency, or sustained load. Those are exactly the conditions where coordination software becomes dangerous if under-tested.\n\n## Deliverables\n- define and close an E2E matrix for restart/replay/recovery paths\n- define and close an E2E matrix for concurrency, contention, and stress scenarios\n- define and close an E2E matrix for dependency failures, degraded modes, and operator-visible recovery behavior\n- ensure failure artifacts are rich enough to debug races, partial writes, retry loops, and degraded-service behavior\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- the repo can point to explicit failure-path and stress-path suites rather than only happy-path workflows\n- restart, retry, and degraded-state correctness are validated at the integration level\n- performance-sensitive or race-sensitive paths have deliberate test coverage rather than folklore\n\n## Important Notes\nThis is the hardening branch of the verification program. It exists to close the confidence gap between “works in the happy path” and “trustworthy under stress.”","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":480,"created_at":"2026-03-18T13:58:29.085494431Z","created_by":"CrimsonSnow","updated_at":"2026-03-18T17:26:54.272431487Z","closed_at":"2026-03-18T17:26:54.271668230Z","close_reason":"Duplicate of br-aazao.11 (same title, same scope). br-aazao.11 is canonical with child subtasks 11.1-11.4.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["e2e","failure","recovery","stress","testing","verification"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-aazao.14","depends_on_id":"br-aazao","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-18T13:58:29.085494431Z","created_by":"CrimsonSnow","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"br-aazao.2","title":"Verification Coverage 1.2: define policy for real-path tests, sanctioned substitutes, and evidence grades","description":"# Verification Coverage 1.2: Define Policy for Real-Path Tests, Sanctioned Substitutes, and Evidence Grades\n\n## Why\nThe phrase “without mocks/fake stuff” is directionally right, but the repo needs a precise operational policy for what that means. Some external or nondeterministic dependencies may still require controlled substitutes, but those exceptions must be explicit, minimized, and never mistaken for full realism.\n\n## Deliverables\n- define evidence grades for tests (real-path, local-realistic fixture, sanctioned substitute, etc.)\n- define which dependency classes must have real-path coverage somewhere in the stack:\n  - SQLite / archive / filesystem / git\n  - MCP stdio / HTTP transport\n  - CLI binaries and install artifacts\n  - TUI / robot / dashboard surfaces\n  - search / embedding / LLM-related paths\n  - share/export crypto and hosting flows\n- define when a substitute is allowed and what additional real-path coverage is required to compensate\n- define annotation / documentation rules for any remaining substitute-based tests\n- define what “coverage closure” means for this repo so later sign-off is objective\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- no future contributor can point to a stub-only test and claim the real path is covered unless the policy explicitly permits that and identifies compensating coverage\n- the policy is concrete enough to guide both unit-test design and E2E design\n- sanctioned substitutes are treated as second-best evidence, not as silent equivalence to real execution\n\n## Important Notes\nThis issue exists to stop future ambiguity. It should make later review disputes short and factual.","status":"open","priority":0,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":180,"created_at":"2026-03-18T13:51:13.704937382Z","created_by":"CrimsonSnow","updated_at":"2026-03-18T13:53:30.484963797Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["coverage","policy","repo-wide","testing","verification"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-aazao.2","depends_on_id":"br-aazao","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-18T13:51:13.704937382Z","created_by":"CrimsonSnow","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-aazao.2","depends_on_id":"br-aazao.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-18T13:53:30.483615457Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
-{"id":"br-aazao.2.1","title":"Verification Coverage 1.2.1: define evidence grades and test realism taxonomy","description":"# Verification Coverage 1.2.1: Define Evidence Grades and Test Realism Taxonomy\n\n## Why\nThe repo needs a shared vocabulary for discussing what a test actually proves. Without that, “integration” and “real” become rhetorical instead of technical terms.\n\n## Deliverables\n- define the realism/evidence taxonomy used across the program\n- provide examples for each grade taken from this repo\n- define how the taxonomy applies across unit, conformance, and E2E lanes\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- review discussions can classify tests quickly and consistently\n- later beads can reuse the taxonomy without redefining it","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":90,"created_at":"2026-03-18T14:01:44.398489495Z","created_by":"CrimsonSnow","updated_at":"2026-03-18T14:01:44.398489495Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["coverage","policy","testing","verification"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-aazao.2.1","depends_on_id":"br-aazao.2","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-18T14:01:44.398489495Z","created_by":"CrimsonSnow","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
