 {"id":"br-aazao.2.2","title":"Verification Coverage 1.2.2: define sanctioned substitute policy and compensation rules","description":"# Verification Coverage 1.2.2: Define Sanctioned Substitute Policy and Compensation Rules\n\n## Why\nSome substitute-based tests may remain useful, but the repo needs explicit rules for when they are allowed and what real-path evidence must exist alongside them.\n\n## Deliverables\n- define allowed substitute classes and disallowed substitute classes\n- define compensating real-path coverage requirements for allowed substitutes\n- define annotation rules so substitute-based tests cannot masquerade as stronger evidence\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- substitute-based tests are deliberately justified rather than casually inherited\n- reviewers can reject under-evidenced substitute usage on objective grounds","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":90,"created_at":"2026-03-18T14:01:55.610406489Z","created_by":"CrimsonSnow","updated_at":"2026-03-18T14:01:55.610406489Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["coverage","policy","realism","testing","verification"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-aazao.2.2","depends_on_id":"br-aazao.2","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-18T14:01:55.610406489Z","created_by":"CrimsonSnow","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"br-aazao.2.3","title":"Verification Coverage 1.2.3: define coverage closure and sign-off criteria","description":"# Verification Coverage 1.2.3: Define Coverage Closure and Sign-Off Criteria\n\n## Why\nThe verification program needs an objective definition of done so future sign-off is evidence-based and not driven by optimism.\n\n## Deliverables\n- define closure criteria by subsystem and test layer\n- define what counts as release-blocking, merge-blocking, or documentation-only debt\n- define the sign-off template used by later CI and final review beads\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- completion of later beads can be evaluated against a fixed rubric\n- the project gains a durable, reviewable definition of verification closure","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":90,"created_at":"2026-03-18T14:04:06.905213111Z","created_by":"CrimsonSnow","updated_at":"2026-03-18T14:04:06.905213111Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["coverage","policy","signoff","testing","verification"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-aazao.2.3","depends_on_id":"br-aazao.2","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-18T14:04:06.905213111Z","created_by":"CrimsonSnow","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"br-aazao.3","title":"Verification Coverage 2.1: replace fake binaries, stub encoders, and mock release artifacts with real-path test inputs","description":"# Verification Coverage 2.1: Replace Fake Binaries, Stub Encoders, and Mock Release Artifacts with Real-Path Test Inputs\n\n## Why\nSeveral current tests derive confidence from obviously synthetic binary or artifact behavior. Those tests are still useful for narrow contracts, but they cannot be the main evidence for install, binary, encoder, or release-path correctness.\n\n## Current Examples To Audit And Burn Down\n- stub encoder scripts in toon integration coverage\n- mock `am` / `mcp-agent-mail` tarballs in installer idempotency coverage\n- synthetic binary behavior that validates wrappers more than real binaries\n\n## Deliverables\n- identify every test that shells out to a fake binary or mock artifact while claiming meaningful end-to-end confidence\n- replace those cases with locally produced real binaries or realistic build artifacts where feasible\n- keep narrow contract tests if still useful, but downgrade their evidentiary status and pair them with real-path coverage\n- ensure installer / self-update / upgrade-path / binary-entrypoint coverage exercises actual built artifacts, not only synthetic stand-ins\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- critical installer or binary lifecycle behavior is no longer validated only by mock artifacts or shell-script impersonations\n- any remaining synthetic binary tests are explicitly justified as contract tests rather than full realism tests\n- later sign-off can point to this issue to justify claims about real binary / artifact verification\n\n## Important Notes\nThe goal is not to ban all fixtures. The goal is to stop fake binaries from masquerading as full end-to-end proof.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","estimated_minutes":300,"created_at":"2026-03-18T13:51:24.414579755Z","created_by":"CrimsonSnow","updated_at":"2026-03-18T13:53:53.688570783Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["coverage","e2e","realism","testing","unit-tests","verification"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"br-aazao.3","depends_on_id":"br-aazao","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-18T13:51:24.414579755Z","created_by":"CrimsonSnow","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-aazao.3","depends_on_id":"br-aazao.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-18T13:53:41.507481884Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"br-aazao.3","depends_on_id":"br-aazao.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-18T13:53:53.687272176Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
